[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 30/100 path 2/8 answer="Let's break it down step by step:\n\n1. Let \\( T \\) be the total number of steps Elliott needed for the day (which we know is 10,000).\n\n2. On his way to and from school, he walked half of his daily goal:\n   \\[ \\frac{T}{2} \\]\n\n3. After walking to and from school, he took another 1,000 steps:\n   \\[ \\frac{T}{2} + 1000 \\]\n\n4. After his short walk with his friend, he completed one-third of what was remaining:\n   \\[ \\frac{1}{3}(T - (\\frac{T}{2} + 1000)) \\]\n\n5. We know that after the jog, he had 2,000 steps left:\n   \\[ \\frac{1}{3}(T - (\\frac{T}{2} + 1000)) = 2000 \\]\n\nNow let's solve for \\( T \\):\n\n\\[\n\\begin{align*}\n\\frac{1}{3}\\left(T - \\frac{T}{2} - 1000\\right) &= 2000 \\\\\n\\frac{1}{3}\\left(\\frac{T}{2} - 1000\\right) &= 2000 \\\\\n\\frac{T}{2} - 1000 &= 6000 \\\\\n\\frac{T}{2} &= 7000 \\\\\nT &= 14000\n\\end{align*}\n\\]\n\nElliott initially wanted to walk 14,000 steps. Now we can find out how many steps he took during his jog.\n\nSince he started at 10,000 steps and ended up needing 2,00"
