[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 43/100 path 4/8 answer="To find out how many popsicle sticks Frederick can make with the cheapest lumber (the 2x4 piece), we first calculate the total number of popsicle sticks he can make with one 2x4:\n\nFrom one 2x4 piece:\n\\[ \\text{Popsicle sticks} = 200 \\]\n\nHe has $24 to spend on wood, so let's determine how many 2x4 pieces he can buy:\n\nPrice of one 2x4 piece: $4\n\nNumber of 2x4 pieces he can buy:\n\\[ \\frac{\\$24}{\\$4} = 6 \\text{ pieces} \\]\n\nNow, we calculate the total number of popsicle sticks he can make from these six 2x4 pieces:\n\n\\[ \\text{Total popsicle sticks} = 6 \\times 200 = 1200 \\]\n\nSo, using the cheapest lumber (2x4 pieces), Frederick can make a maximum of 1200 popsicle sticks."
