[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 78/100 path 6/8 answer='Let \\( S \\) represent the number of small stuffed animals sold, and let \\( L \\) represent the number of large stuffed animals sold.\n\nFrom the problem statement:\n1. Teresa earns $120 from selling small and large stuffed animals.\n2. Small stuffed animals cost $4 each.\n3. Large stuffed animals cost \\( 3 \\times 4 = \\$12 \\) each (since they are sold for three times the price of small stuffed animals).\n\nGiven information translates into equations:\n\\[\n4S + 12L = 120 \\quad \\text{(Equation 1)}\n\\]\n\\[\nS = 2L \\quad \\text{(Equation 2)} \\quad \\text{[Teresa sold twice as many small stuffed animals as large ones]}\n\\]\n\nSubstituting Equation 2 into Equation 1:\n\n\\[\n4(2L) + 12L = 120\n\\]\n\nSimplify:\n\\[\n8L + 12L = 120 \\\\\n20L = 120 \\\\\nL = \\frac{120}{20} \\\\\nL = 6\n\\]\n\nSo, Teresa sold 6 large stuffed animals.\n\nUsing Equation 2 to find how many small stuffed animals were sold:\n\\[\nS = 2L = 2 \\times 6 = 12\n\\]\n\nTherefore, Teresa sold 12 small stuffed animals today.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 78/100 path 7/8 start
