[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 82/100 path 3/8 start
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 82/100 path 3/8 answer='Let \\( x \\) represent the total number of jellyfish initially in the tank.\n\nA fifth of the jellyfish are large:\n\\[ \\frac{1}{5}x \\]\n\nA third of these large jellyfish change color:\n\\[ \\frac{1}{3} \\times \\left(\\frac{1}{5}x\\right) = \\frac{1}{15}x \\]\n\nThe rest of the jellyfish (small ones) remain unchanged:\n\\[ x - \\frac{1}{5}x - \\frac{1}{15}x \\]\n\nGiven that when the UV light was turned on, 6 jellyfish changed color:\n\nWe have:\n\\[ \\frac{1}{15}x + 6 = x \\]\n\nSolving this equation:\n\\[ \\frac{1}{15}x + 6 = x \\]\n\\[ 6 = x - \\frac{1}{15}x \\]\n\\[ 6 = \\frac{14}{15}x \\]\n\\[ x = \\frac{6 \\times 15}{14} \\]\n\\[ x = \\frac{90}{14} \\]\n\\[ x = \\frac{45}{7} \\approx 6.4286 \\]\n\nSince \\( x \\) represents whole jellyfish, we round down to the nearest whole number:\n\\[ x = 6 \\]\n\nTherefore, there are 6 jellyfish in the tank originally.\n\nFinally, calculating how many were large and thus would change color with the UV light:\n\\[ \\frac{1}{5} \\times 6 = 1.2 \\]\n\nThere were 1 large jellyfish that would change color, so subtract those from the total count of jellyfish:\n\\[ 6 - 1 = 5 \\]\n\nHence, 5 large jellyfish would change color'
