[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 82/100 path 5/8 answer='Let \\( J \\) represent the total number of jellyfish in the tank. According to the problem:\n\\[ \\frac{1}{5}J + \\frac{1}{3}\\left(\\frac{1}{5}J\\right) = 6 \\]\n\nFirst, simplify the equation:\n\\[ \\frac{1}{5}J + \\frac{1}{15}J = 6 \\]\n\nCombine the fractions:\n\\[ \\frac{3}{15}J + \\frac{1}{15}J = 6 \\]\n\\[ \\frac{4}{15}J = 6 \\]\n\nSolve for \\( J \\):\n\\[ J = 6 \\times \\frac{15}{4} \\]\n\\[ J = \\frac{90}{4} \\]\n\\[ J = 22.5 \\]\n\nSince the number of jellyfish must be a whole number, we can conclude there are 22 jellyfish (as fractional jellyfish are not possible).\n\nNow calculate the number of large and small jellyfish:\n\nLarge Jellyfish (\\( L \\)):\n\\[ \\frac{1}{5} \\text{of } J = \\frac{1}{5} \\times 22 = 4.4 \\]\nSince the count should be a whole number, rounding to nearest integer gives us 4 large jellyfish.\n\nSmall Jellyfish (\\( S \\)):\n\\[ J - L = 22 - 4 = 18 \\]\n\nThus, the remaining 18 jellyfish are small and will always remain blue.\n\nTo verify, check if adding these numbers aligns with the given information about the changes when exposed to UV light:\n\\[ \\frac{1}{5} \\times 22 + \\frac{1}{3} \\times 4 = 4.4 + 1.333 ='
