[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 1/100 path 3/3 answer="Let's denote the total number of vacuum cleaners Melanie started with as \\( X \\).\n\nAfter selling a third of them:\n\\( \\frac{X}{3} \\) vacuum cleaners were sold.\n\nSo there were initially \\( \\frac{2X}{3} \\) vacuum cleaners available to leave behind after selling one-third.\n\nNext, 2 more vacuum cleaners were sold from the remaining ones at the red house:\n\\( \\frac{2X}{3} - 2 \\)\n\nThen she sold half of the rest at the orange house:\n\\( \\left(\\frac{2X}{3} - 2\\right) \\times \\frac{1}{2} = \\frac{X}{3} - 1 \\)\n\nAfter that sale, she had some vacuum cleaners left:\n\\( \\frac{X}{3} - 1 \\), which we know is equal to 5 because she now has 5 vacuum cleaners left.\n\nNow let's solve it algebraically:\n\nFirst part left: \\( \\frac{2X}{3} - 2 \\)\nRemaining before orange sale: \\( \\frac{2X}{3} - 2 - 5 = \\frac{X}{3} - 7 \\)\n\nWe know that after these two sales, the number left should match our previous result (remaining before orange sale). So we set them equal:\n\n\\( \\frac{X}{3} - 7 = \\frac{X}{3} - 1 \\)\n\nTo find \\( X \\):\nAdd 1 to both sides:\n\\( \\frac{X}{3} - 1 = 0 \\)\n\nAdd 1 on both sides:\n\\( \\frac{X}{3} = 1 \\)\n\nMultiply both sides by 3:\n\\( X = 3 \\times 1 = 3 \\)\n\nTherefore, Melanie originally had 3 vacuum cleaners.\n\nThe answer is"
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 1/100 done id=gsm8k_test_13 prediction='18' gold='18' correct=True vote_counts={'18': 1, '13': 1, "Let's denote the total number of vacuum cleaners Melanie started with as \\( X \\).\n\nAfter selling a third of them:\n\\( \\frac{X}{3} \\) vacuum cleaners were sold.\n\nSo there were initially \\( \\frac{2X}{3} \\) vacuum cleaners available to leave behind after selling one-third.\n\nNext, 2 more vacuum cleaners were sold from the remaining ones at the red house:\n\\( \\frac{2X}{3} - 2 \\)\n\nThen she sold half of the rest at the orange house:\n\\( \\left(\\frac{2X}{3} - 2\\right) \\times \\frac{1}{2} = \\frac{X}{3} - 1 \\)\n\nAfter that sale, she had some vacuum cleaners left:\n\\( \\frac{X}{3} - 1 \\), which we know is equal to 5 because she now has 5 vacuum cleaners left.\n\nNow let's solve it algebraically:\n\nFirst part left: \\( \\frac{2X}{3} - 2 \\)\nRemaining before orange sale: \\( \\frac{2X}{3} - 2 - 5 = \\frac{X}{3} - 7 \\)\n\nWe know that after these two sales, the number left should match our previous result (remaining before orange sale). So we set them equal:\n\n\\( \\frac{X}{3} - 7 = \\frac{X}{3} - 1 \\)\n\nTo find \\( X \\):\nAdd 1 to both sides:\n\\( \\frac{X}{3} - 1 = 0 \\)\n\nAdd 1 on both sides:\n\\( \\frac{X}{3} = 1 \\)\n\nMultiply both sides by 3:\n\\( X = 3 \\times 1 = 3 \\)\n\nTherefore, Melanie originally had 3 vacuum cleaners.\n\nThe answer is": 1}
