[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 13/100 path 1/3 answer="We know that three action figures weigh the same as a single doll, so:\n$$doll\\weight \\quad=3(action\\fig\\ weight)=$$  \nA red car weighs $4$, so four red cars (one doll and three action figures) weigh:\n$$red\\car \\cdot 4=doll+action\\fig=4\\times4=16($$  \nTherefore, the total value of all the toys is:\n$$toys=\\dollars\\of\\dolls +\\dollars\\of[action\\ figs]=doll\\weight+dollars\\of[doll]=doll\\weight+(doll\\color{magenta}{cost}+dollars\\of[\\dollars\\of[action\\ figs})]=$$\n\n$$=doll\\weight+(\\dollars\\of[doll] +\\dollars\\of[action\\ figs])+dollars\\of[action\\ figs]=$$\nAdding all those terms together gives us:\n\n$$\\begin{align}\ntotal &=doll\\weight+(\\dollars\\of[doll] +dollars\\of[action\\ figs]) \\\\\n     &=(doll\\weight+\\dollarstoof[action\\ figs]+dollars\\of[act\\ figs])\n     =(doll\\weight+dollars\\of[doll]+\\dollars\\of[action\\ figs])+\n    (dollars\\of[doll]+\\dollars\\of[action\\ figs])\\\\\n     &=(doll\\weight+dollars\\of[doll]+\\dollars\\of[action\\ figs]+dollars\\of[doll]+\\dollars\\of[action\\ figs])\n\\end{align}$$\n\nSubstituting known values into the equation allows you calculate it. Since each toy's price is provided, these will cancel out with the corresponding dollar symbols:\n\n$$total = 1(4)+5=9 dollars$$"
