[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 25/100 path 2/3 answer="Let P represent the number of people who got on the bus at the terminal initially.\n\nAt the first bus stop:\nP + 5 people got on\n\nAt the second bus stop:\n(P + 5) - 7 people got off, and (P + 5) + 8 people got on\nSo there were 20 people left,\n\nWe can set up the equation:\n(P + 5) - 7 + (P + 5) + 8 = 20\n\nCombining like terms:\n\n2P + 9 = 20\n\nSubtract 9 from both sides:\n2P = 11\n\nDivide by 2:\nP = 5.5\n\nSince the number of people should be whole numbers,\nwe conclude that there was no mistake in setting up our steps or calculations because the math would break if we used fractions.\nIt appears the provided calculation had an error.\n\nTherefore, let's directly solve it using correct logic:\nTotal passengers after the second stop before subtracting is 5 (from terminal) + 8 (second bus stop), which sums up to 13 people. But since there were actually 20, and they subtracted 7, but didn't include those 8 back in their original count:\n\nTerminal -> First busstop -> Second busstop\n\nSo adding them all together gives us:\n\n5 initial passengers\nPlus 5 from first stop\nPlus another 5 from the end\n\nThat's 15 people in total. \n\nThey have 5 less than needed to reach 20:\n\n20 needed - 5 available = 15 people missing from the current total\n\nThus, when combining 15 with 5 (at terminal):\n\nFinal amount equals 20\n\nHowever, we see my last calculation seems flawed without explicitly addressing what happened between stops where people get off and arrive.\n\nTo"
