[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 43/100 done id=gsm8k_test_505 prediction='Frederick initially gets 200 sticks with a 2 x 4 piece of wood costing $4 and 400 sticks with a 2 x 8 piece of wood costing $6.\nTo find the cost-effectiveness ratio per stick, we calculate:\nCost of sticks from each type divided by number of sticks:\nFor 2 x 4 pieces: \nCost = 200 / 4 = $<<200/4=50>>50\nNumber of sticks per dollar spent = 200 / 50 = <<200/50=4>>4\n\nFor 2 x 8 pieces:\nCost = 400 / 6 ≈ $<<400/6=66.67>>66.67 (rounded down)\nNumber of sticks per dollar spent = 400 / 66.67 ≈ 6\nSince Frederick aims to spend $24 on wood:\n\nFor 2 x 4 pieces:\nTotal cost = 1 piece * $4 = $<<1*4=4>>4\n\nRemaining money after buying wood is $24 - $4 = $<<24-4=20>>20.\nWith $20, Frederick can purchase up to 20 / 50 * 4 = <<20/50*4=1.6>>1.6 more sets of 2 x 4 wood, which rounds down to 1 set.\nHence, total popsicle sticks he can make = Initial sticks + Additional sticks = 200 + 100 = <<200+100=300>>300.\n\nFor 2 x 8 pieces:\nUsing remaining $20 to buy additional sets of 2 x 8:\nTotal additional' gold='1600' correct=False vote_counts={'Frederick initially gets 200 sticks with a 2 x 4 piece of wood costing $4 and 400 sticks with a 2 x 8 piece of wood costing $6.\nTo find the cost-effectiveness ratio per stick, we calculate:\nCost of sticks from each type divided by number of sticks:\nFor 2 x 4 pieces: \nCost = 200 / 4 = $<<200/4=50>>50\nNumber of sticks per dollar spent = 200 / 50 = <<200/50=4>>4\n\nFor 2 x 8 pieces:\nCost = 400 / 6 ≈ $<<400/6=66.67>>66.67 (rounded down)\nNumber of sticks per dollar spent = 400 / 66.67 ≈ 6\nSince Frederick aims to spend $24 on wood:\n\nFor 2 x 4 pieces:\nTotal cost = 1 piece * $4 = $<<1*4=4>>4\n\nRemaining money after buying wood is $24 - $4 = $<<24-4=20>>20.\nWith $20, Frederick can purchase up to 20 / 50 * 4 = <<20/50*4=1.6>>1.6 more sets of 2 x 4 wood, which rounds down to 1 set.\nHence, total popsicle sticks he can make = Initial sticks + Additional sticks = 200 + 100 = <<200+100=300>>300.\n\nFor 2 x 8 pieces:\nUsing remaining $20 to buy additional sets of 2 x 8:\nTotal additional': 1, '1200': 1, '600': 1}
