[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 45/100 path 2/3 answer="If Elvis wants to save twice as much daily in the second half, we can denote his daily savings in the second half as \\(2x\\) where \\(x\\) is his daily savings in the first half.\n\nFirst, find the total number of days in April:\n\\[ 30 \\text{ days} \\]\n\nFor simplicity, assume a standard month with 30 days and break it down into two equal halves (first half and second half). Each half would then have:\n\n\\[ \\frac{30}{2} = 15 \\text{ days} \\]\n\nIn the first half of April, Elvis saves:\n\\[ 15x \\]\n\nIn the second half of April, Elvis saves twice as much:\n\\[ 2(15x) = 30x \\]\n\nTotal savings in April:\n\\[ 15x + 30x = 45x \\]\n\nWe know his goal is to save $1125 throughout all months combined and assuming every day contributes equally to that sum, let's set up our equation for the total savings:\n\n\\[ 30x + 30x = 1125 \\]\n\\[ 60x = 1125 \\]\n\\[ x = \\frac{1125}{60} \\]\n\nNow calculate how much Elvis saves on each day in the first half:\n\\[ x = \\frac{1125}{60} = 18.75 \\]\n\nElvis’s daily savings in the first half should contribute towards his goal; thus, his required saving amount is \\(15\\) x \\(18.75\\):\n\\[ 15 * 18.75 = \\$<15*18.75=281.25>\n\nSo, each day Elvis has to save $<281."
