[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 47/100 path 3/3 answer="Elise writes all the letters of the alphabet once, so that's 26 letters. That takes up 1 section. Then she takes one half off this and doubles it back on herself. That gives her another 26 letters (half the length of the original alphabet) but since each letter counts double now because she had already taken them out of the original count, those take up .5 sections worth of space.\n\nNow she repeats this process from when we started with putting down the whole alphabet. We have accounted for a 1/2 letter at this point. Thus there is yet another set of half the alphabet to write again. That will also occupy another .5 section.\n\nSo we'll account for 1 + .5 + .5 or 1.5 total sections.\n\nMultiplying that number by 26 letters per section, we see that the total amount of time Elise took to complete this task was 13(whole) + 13(half)\n\nIn summary,\n<answer>39</answer>"
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 47/100 done id=gsm8k_test_546 prediction='65' gold='130' correct=False vote_counts={'65': 1, '208': 1, "Elise writes all the letters of the alphabet once, so that's 26 letters. That takes up 1 section. Then she takes one half off this and doubles it back on herself. That gives her another 26 letters (half the length of the original alphabet) but since each letter counts double now because she had already taken them out of the original count, those take up .5 sections worth of space.\n\nNow she repeats this process from when we started with putting down the whole alphabet. We have accounted for a 1/2 letter at this point. Thus there is yet another set of half the alphabet to write again. That will also occupy another .5 section.\n\nSo we'll account for 1 + .5 + .5 or 1.5 total sections.\n\nMultiplying that number by 26 letters per section, we see that the total amount of time Elise took to complete this task was 13(whole) + 13(half)\n\nIn summary,\n<answer>39</answer>": 1}
