[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 66/100 done id=gsm8k_test_777 prediction='4000' gold='4400' correct=False vote_counts={'4000': 1, 'Mike initially has 600 movies, so the number of movies in series is 600/3 = 200.\nHe can trade these series for free at $6 for every $10 worth of normal movies.\nTo find out how many sets of three movies (one normal + two from series) he can get for his entire collection, we first calculate how many such groups he can obtain:\n600 movies total / (3 "movies" per group) = 200 groups\n\nNow let\'s calculate the total cost:\nEach group is traded away for free but still requires one purchase of three items,\neach costing $10.\nSince he gets free the cost of two movies for each purchase of the third movie,\nhe saves $10 on the price of every 3 movies purchased.\n\nTherefore, the total savings per set of three movies is 3 items priced at $10 minus $6 (cost of trade): \n30 dollars minus $6 equals $24 saved per group.\nIf there are 200 groups available,\nthen the total additional amount Mike paid beyond what a single movie normally costs would be: \n200 groups multiplied by $24 per group: \n200 * $24 equals $<<200*24=4800>>4800.\n\nSubtracting the savings gives us the total replacement fee:\nTotal original cost subtracted savings,\ni.e.,\n$10 multiplied by 600 movies since that\'s how many he initially owns: \n10 * 600 equals $<<10*600=6000>>6000.\nNow subtracting all expenses we found before yields:\n\n6000 - 4800 = $<<6000-4800=1200': 1, '2440': 1}
