[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 82/100 path 1/3 answer='Let \\( T \\) represent the total number of jellyfish in the tank.\nA fifth of the jellyfish are large, so we have:\n\\[ \\frac{1}{5}T \\text{ large jellyfish} \\]\nA third of these large jellyfish change color, thus:\n\\[ \\frac{1}{3} \\times \\frac{1}{5}T = \\frac{1}{15}T \\text{ large jellyfish turn blue}\n\\]\nThe remaining jellyfish (the others) remain uncolored, i.e., \n\\[ T - \\frac{1}{5}T = \\frac{4}{5}T \\text{ are small}\n\\]\n\nAccording to the problem, \\( \\frac{4}{5}T = 6 \\):\n\\[ \\frac{4}{5}T = 6 \\]\nWe solve for \\( T \\):\n\\[ T = \\frac{6 \\times 5}{4} = 7.5 \\]\n\nSince the number of jellyfish must be whole numbers, \\( T = 7.5 \\) indicates there was an error with the setup or calculation steps above; reevaluate carefully.\n\nRevisiting the initial breakdown:\n- Large jellyfish = \\(\\frac{1}{5}T\\)  \n- Large turning blue = \\(\\frac{1}{3}\\), thus large needing recalculating properly: \\[ T - \\left( \\frac{1}{3} \\times \\frac{1}{5}T + \\frac{2}{3} \\cdot \\frac{1}{5}T \\right) \\]\nSolving correct calculations leads to larger consistent equations, recalculated correctly:\n\nGiven 6 blue jellyfish from 4/5x=total:\n\\[ 7.5 - 6 = .5x \\] Jellyfish size analysis correct recalibration confirms'
