[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 82/100 path 3/3 answer='Let \\( L \\) represent the number of large jellyfish, and \\( S \\) represent the number of small jellyfish. According to the problem:\n\n\\[\nL = \\frac{1}{5} T\n\\]\n\nwhere \\( T \\) represents the total number of jellyfish.\n\nWe know:\n\n1. Large jellyfish account for one-fifth of the total number of jellyfish.\n2. A third of the large jellyfish change color when exposed to UV light.\n3. There were 6 jellyfish that changed color.\n4. Each of these changes was made due to UV lighting exposure on all jellyfish, regardless of their initial color status or size.\n  \nFrom point 4, we can infer that 6 is three times the number of large jellyfish since a third of them turns blue. Therefore:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{1}{3}L = 6 \\\\\n\\Rightarrow L = 6 \\times 3 \\\\\n\\Rightarrow L = 18\n\\]\n\nNow substituting back to find total number of jellyfish using point 1, \n\n\\[\nT = 5L \\\\\n\\Rightarrow T = 5 \\times 18 \\\\\n\\Rightarrow T = 90 \n\\]\n\nThus, the total number of jellyfish in the tank is **90**.'
[self_consistency][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][gsm8k] sample 82/100 done id=gsm8k_test_1103 prediction='Let \\( T \\) represent the total number of jellyfish in the tank.\nA fifth of the jellyfish are large, so we have:\n\\[ \\frac{1}{5}T \\text{ large jellyfish} \\]\nA third of these large jellyfish change color, thus:\n\\[ \\frac{1}{3} \\times \\frac{1}{5}T = \\frac{1}{15}T \\text{ large jellyfish turn blue}\n\\]\nThe remaining jellyfish (the others) remain uncolored, i.e., \n\\[ T - \\frac{1}{5}T = \\frac{4}{5}T \\text{ are small}\n\\]\n\nAccording to the problem, \\( \\frac{4}{5}T = 6 \\):\n\\[ \\frac{4}{5}T = 6 \\]\nWe solve for \\( T \\):\n\\[ T = \\frac{6 \\times 5}{4} = 7.5 \\]\n\nSince the number of jellyfish must be whole numbers, \\( T = 7.5 \\) indicates there was an error with the setup or calculation steps above; reevaluate carefully.\n\nRevisiting the initial breakdown:\n- Large jellyfish = \\(\\frac{1}{5}T\\)  \n- Large turning blue = \\(\\frac{1}{3}\\), thus large needing recalculating properly: \\[ T - \\left( \\frac{1}{3} \\times \\frac{1}{5}T + \\frac{2}{3} \\cdot \\frac{1}{5}T \\right) \\]\nSolving correct calculations leads to larger consistent equations, recalculated correctly:\n\nGiven 6 blue jellyfish from 4/5x=total:\n\\[ 7.5 - 6 = .5x \\] Jellyfish size analysis correct recalibration confirms' gold='90' correct=False vote_counts={'Let \\( T \\) represent the total number of jellyfish in the tank.\nA fifth of the jellyfish are large, so we have:\n\\[ \\frac{1}{5}T \\text{ large jellyfish} \\]\nA third of these large jellyfish change color, thus:\n\\[ \\frac{1}{3} \\times \\frac{1}{5}T = \\frac{1}{15}T \\text{ large jellyfish turn blue}\n\\]\nThe remaining jellyfish (the others) remain uncolored, i.e., \n\\[ T - \\frac{1}{5}T = \\frac{4}{5}T \\text{ are small}\n\\]\n\nAccording to the problem, \\( \\frac{4}{5}T = 6 \\):\n\\[ \\frac{4}{5}T = 6 \\]\nWe solve for \\( T \\):\n\\[ T = \\frac{6 \\times 5}{4} = 7.5 \\]\n\nSince the number of jellyfish must be whole numbers, \\( T = 7.5 \\) indicates there was an error with the setup or calculation steps above; reevaluate carefully.\n\nRevisiting the initial breakdown:\n- Large jellyfish = \\(\\frac{1}{5}T\\)  \n- Large turning blue = \\(\\frac{1}{3}\\), thus large needing recalculating properly: \\[ T - \\left( \\frac{1}{3} \\times \\frac{1}{5}T + \\frac{2}{3} \\cdot \\frac{1}{5}T \\right) \\]\nSolving correct calculations leads to larger consistent equations, recalculated correctly:\n\nGiven 6 blue jellyfish from 4/5x=total:\n\\[ 7.5 - 6 = .5x \\] Jellyfish size analysis correct recalibration confirms': 1, '6': 1, 'Let \\( L \\) represent the number of large jellyfish, and \\( S \\) represent the number of small jellyfish. According to the problem:\n\n\\[\nL = \\frac{1}{5} T\n\\]\n\nwhere \\( T \\) represents the total number of jellyfish.\n\nWe know:\n\n1. Large jellyfish account for one-fifth of the total number of jellyfish.\n2. A third of the large jellyfish change color when exposed to UV light.\n3. There were 6 jellyfish that changed color.\n4. Each of these changes was made due to UV lighting exposure on all jellyfish, regardless of their initial color status or size.\n  \nFrom point 4, we can infer that 6 is three times the number of large jellyfish since a third of them turns blue. Therefore:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{1}{3}L = 6 \\\\\n\\Rightarrow L = 6 \\times 3 \\\\\n\\Rightarrow L = 18\n\\]\n\nNow substituting back to find total number of jellyfish using point 1, \n\n\\[\nT = 5L \\\\\n\\Rightarrow T = 5 \\times 18 \\\\\n\\Rightarrow T = 90 \n\\]\n\nThus, the total number of jellyfish in the tank is **90**.': 1}
